@startuml
title Threat model — data-flow diagram with trust boundaries
$Subtitle("STRIDE anchors: every crossing of a dashed boundary is an attack surface")

left to right direction

actor "Integrator\n(holds X-API-Key)" as Client
actor "Operator\n(browser on host)" as Operator

rectangle "Trust boundary: Docker network" as TB1 {
  [api\nFastAPI\nauth · rate limit · validation] as Api
  database "postgres\nsingle app role (DDL+DML)" as Pg
  [prometheus] as Prom
  [elasticsearch] as ES
}

rectangle "Trust boundary: host filesystem" as TB2 {
  artifact "NDJSON logs\n(may contain request context)" as Logs
  artifact "./var/postgres volume\n(unencrypted, no backup)" as Vol
}

cloud "GitHub" as GH

Client --> Api : HTTPS · JSON\n[S] spoofed key · [D] retry storm
Api --> Pg : SQL\n[T] bypass validation · [E] DDL from app role
Pg --> Vol : data at rest\n[I] volume read = full disclosure
Api --> Logs : append\n[I] log leakage · [R] gap in audit
Prom ..> Api : scrape /metrics\n[I] metric names leak topology
ES ..> Logs : ingest via filebeat
Operator --> ES : Kibana (no auth on stand)
Operator --> Prom : Grafana
GH ..> Api : CI artefacts\n[T] supply chain (deps, images)

note bottom of Vol
  Highest-impact asset.
  Controls: gitignored, network-isolated.
  Open: encryption, backup policy (ADR 0037).
end note

note bottom of Api
  Enforcement point for every client-side [S]/[D]:
  X-API-Key, per-key rate limit, body-size cap,
  404-not-403 on cross-tenant reads.
end note

@enduml
